{"source_key":"sha256-2d2d576cbb8cdfc20bcefa53588d7eed","record_index":26,"record_hash":"sha256:a2d7d61da02f57211230289e04a070bf3e32f34810c7ae6622d06ab2e81f1bb2","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:14:43.601Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: e5baa9\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 3555\nOutput:\n\nCommit file collection should be path-only. We need the set of changed relative\npaths, not patches, hunks, line stats, or blob-level content diffs. A commit does\nnot directly store \"changed files\", so implementation still needs a tree\ncomparison between the commit tree and its first parent tree, but it should use a\ncheap tree-delta path walk and avoid UI diff APIs or unified diff generation.\nFor root commits, compare against an empty tree. For merge commits, use the\nfirst-parent comparison for v1.\n\nFor renames or rewrites, the path evidence set should include every observed\npath side that is available. If rename detection is disabled for speed and Git\nreports the change as a deletion plus an addition, that is acceptable for v1\nbecause both paths still appear as evidence.\n\nIf a list exceeds the cap, store the first capped set in deterministic sorted\norder plus the total count and `*_truncated = true`. Path hashes can be added\nlater if matching beyond the cap becomes necessary, but they should not be part\nof the first shape.\n\nDo not store commit message summaries in the turn snapshot. Commit subjects can\nbe read from Git by `commit_id` when a UI needs them, and they are not useful\nassociation evidence.\n\nSnapshot status values:\n\n- `complete`: worktree and stack/branch observations were collected\n- `partial`: some observations were collected but one or more optional pieces\n  failed\n- `failed`: no useful environment observation was collected\n\nFor failed or partial snapshots, store a coarse `error_kind` if useful for\ndebugging or telemetry, such as `context_unavailable`, `workspace_unavailable`,\nor `diff_unavailable`. Do not store raw error strings in the shared turn\nmetadata by default.\n\nConcrete turn detail example:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"schema\": \"gitbutler.agent-session-turn.v1\",\n  \"turn_key\": \"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\n  \"session_key\": \"sha256-1122334455667788\",\n  \"source_key\": \"sha256-9988776655443322\",\n  \"prev\n[TRUNCATED]\nookup indexes:** persisted materialized views for fast candidate\n  discovery, safe to rebuild when heuristics change\n- **association result:** computed on read from candidates plus observations,\n  with reasons and heuristic/schema version\n\nThis means association work is split across write and read time:\n\n- **Capture time:** write observations and deterministic index memberships from\n  the current turn snapshot, such as observed branch names, review ids, and\n  change ids.\n- **Read time:** answer association questions by looking up candidate turns from\n  indexes, reading their observations, and scoring/explaining likely related\n  sessions with the current heuristic version.\n\nCapture should not write final inferred relationships such as \"this PR is\nassociated with this session\" or \"this branch was produced by this session.\"\nIt only writes the facts and lookup entries needed to answer those questions\nefficiently later.\n\nThe index is not the association. It is a disposable acceleration structure.\nIf the heuristic changes, rebuild the index and old sessions can benefit\nretroactively.\n\nFor v1, write only branch, review, and change indexes:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agentlog-index-version = 1\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:branch:<branch-key> = set<session-key/turn-key>\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:review:<review-key> = set<session-key/turn-key>\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:change:<change-id> = set<session-key/turn-key>\n```\n\nThe index value includes both the session key and turn key so an index lookup can\nresolve directly to the owning session without scanning session turn lists.\nBranch and review index key material should be safe for GitMeta keys; hashing\nbranch/review values is acceptable as long as the readable values remain in the\nturn snapshot. Change ids are already compact, durable identifiers and can be\nused directly unless the GitMeta key rules require escaping.\n\nDo not write a path index in v1. Path-level keys can explode with large commits,\nbroad worktree changes, generated files, or dependency lockfile churn. File\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:14:43.601Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}